post_title: Past, Present, and a maybe Future
post_text:
How does one start over?
 It's not an easy thing after you've spent half your life with someone. Marriage, home, kids, then as if it happens over night, it's all gone. You feel like you gave everything for so long that there's virtually nothing left of yourself. And all that's left behind is an emptiness in the pit of your stomach and your soul. Every day you wake up, look in the mirror and have to convince yourself that you're not afraid even though all you see in the reflection is fear and maybe even some self hate. Finally one morning you take a deep breath and tell yourself enough, you're better then that, all the scars, blood, sweat and tears, you're still alive. You still have a life to live and that can be the hardest fact to face. 
 So finally one morning you start to like yourself again and each day you work at trying to see a future. Reality of it all is that even when you're ready and want to move on, finding ways to do so is like finding your way out of maze with no exits, and all the paths lead to where you don't want to go. The more you look the less attractive some of the options become. Examples, bars and clubs, ARE YOU KIDDING, I can't see myself sitting there staring into an empty glass or bottle using liquid courage to meet someone. You're more likely to become an alcoholic first. There are activities I guess, both organized and not, that for the most part (in my opinion) seem like a gathering of the most extreme in desperation. Like a piece of meat in the middle of a pack of starved wolves, you're either the meat or one of the wolves, and the thought of being either just turns your stomach. And worse of all, "Social Media", the information age, internet dating, Facebook, date sites, craigslist, the absolute extreme of not just a needle in hay stack but the one needle in a hay stack of nothing but other needles. One hundred percent impersonal yet all of you is exposed on display for all to see. You almost hope for complete anonymity and at the same time hoping someone sees, accepts and even gives you that little glance or the slightest smile as if they can see you for who you can and want to be. 
 Now I ask myself what is it I want for just that one person to ultimately see in me and me in that one person. Ideally, a person who we both see each other as like that the first cup of coffee in the morning. Every day a new beginning opening your eyes to possibilities, warming you, and awakening you to every new day. Ultimately there's a calmness that gives you hope.
